Email Sentinel: Spam Detection Using ML & NLP

Introduction:

Spam emails pose a significant security risk and can overwhelm users with unwanted content, phishing attempts, and malicious links. To address this issue, this project presents an intelligent Spam Detection System that leverages Natural Language Processing (NLP) and Machine Learning techniques to classify emails as either spam or legitimate (ham). The system analyzes email content through word-frequency features and engineered text attributes, balances data using SMOTE to handle class imbalance, and trains predictive models such as Logistic Regression and Multinomial Naive Bayes. Comprehensive evaluation metricsincluding accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, confusion matrix, and ROC curvedemonstrate the effectiveness of the models in identifying spam with high reliability. This solution showcases a practical, scalable, and data-driven approach to enhancing email security and improving user inbox experience.

Problem Statement:-

Email remains one of the most widely used communication tools, but it is also a primary channel for delivering spam, phishing attacks, and malicious content. Detecting these spam emails manually is inefficient and often impossible due to the massive volume of messages received daily. Traditional rule-based filters are no longer sufficient because spammers continuously evolve their techniques. Therefore, there is a growing need for an intelligent, automated, and data-driven system that can accurately classify emails as spam or legitimate. This project aims to address this challenge by building a machine learningbased spam detection model capable of learning from historical email patterns and identifying spam with high accuracy.

Project Objectives

  1. Analyze and preprocess email data using feature extraction and engineered attributes.
  2. Balance the dataset using SMOTE to handle class imbalance.
  3. Build and train machine learning models, including Logistic Regression and Multinomial Naive Bayes.
  4. Evaluate model performance using metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, confusion matrix, and ROC curve.
  5. Compare the models to identify which approach performs best for spam detection
  6. Develop a reliable, scalable, and automated solution for detecting spam emails.

1. Setup & Load Data

This section of the project initializes all essential libraries and configurations required for building the spam detection system. It imports core data processing packages such as pandas, numpy, and visualization tools like matplotlib and seaborn for exploratory data analysis and graphical insights. Additionally, text preprocessing utilitiesincluding re, string, and advanced NLP libraries such as NLTK and TextBlobare loaded to support tokenization, lemmatization, stopword removal, and sentiment-based operations. The code also imports scikit-learn modules like train_test_split and TfidfVectorizer to prepare the dataset and transform text into numerical features suitable for machine learning. Essential NLTK resources (tokenizers, stopwords, wordnet, POS tagger) are downloaded to enable advanced linguistic processing. Finally, the environment is configured with consistent display settings, visualization styles, and fixed random seeds to ensure reproducibility throughout the project.

Compute Message Length (Total Word Count per Email):-

This code creates a new feature called message_length, which represents the total word frequency for each email. Since the dataset contains word-count columns for thousands of terms, the code calculates the sum of all these word-frequency values across each row while excluding non-text columns such as "Email No." and "Prediction". This aggregated value indicates how long or dense each email is, making it a useful engineered feature for spam classification. After computing the new feature, the final line displays the first few values of the message_length column to verify that it has been added correctly and contains meaningful data.

In[]:
df["message_length"] = df.drop(columns=["Email No.", "Prediction"]).sum(axis=1)

Word Cloud for Spam Emails

This code generates a visual word cloud representing the most frequently occurring words in spam emails. First, the dataset is filtered to include only rows where the prediction class is 1 (Spam). All non-text columns (Email No., Prediction, and message_length) are removed, leaving only the bag-of-words features. The total frequency of each word is calculated and converted into a dictionary, which serves as input for the WordCloud generator. Using these frequencies, the WordCloud library creates a graphic where more frequent words appear larger and bolder. The resulting image is displayed with Matplotlib, accompanied by a title Word Cloud Spam Emails. This visualization helps highlight the strongest textual patterns in spam messages and provides quick insight into the vocabulary commonly used in malicious or promotional content.

In[]:
from wordcloud import WordCloud

spam_df = df[df["Prediction"] == 1]
spam_bow = spam_df.drop(columns=["Email No.", "Prediction", "message_length"])

spam_freq = spam_bow.sum().to_dict()

wordcloud_spam = WordCloud(width=800, height=400, background_color="white").generate_from_frequencies(spam_freq)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.imshow(wordcloud_spam, interpolation="bilinear")
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Word Cloud - Spam Emails")
plt.show()

3. Text Preprocessing

Define Helper Functions:-

This function, get_wordnet_pos, is used to map NLTKs part-of-speech (POS) tags to the format required by WordNet, which improves the accuracy of lemmatization. Since WordNet expects specific POS categories such as noun, verb, adjective, or adverb, this function first checks the first letter of the POS tag generated by NLTK. If the tag starts with J, it is classified as an adjective; V indicates a verb; N is mapped to a noun; and R corresponds to an adverb. Any tag that does not match these cases defaults to a noun. By converting the POS tags into WordNet-compatible formats, this function ensures that words are lemmatized more intelligentlyfor example, running becomes run when treated as a verb instead of a noun. This significantly improves the quality of text preprocessing in NLP tasks.

In[]:
from nltk.corpus import wordnet

def get_wordnet_pos(tag):
    if tag.startswith('J'):
        return wordnet.ADJ
    elif tag.startswith('V'):
        return wordnet.VERB
    elif tag.startswith('N'):
        return wordnet.NOUN
    elif tag.startswith('R'):
        return wordnet.ADV
    else:
        return wordnet.NOUN

Cleaning Function:-

The clean_text function performs fundamental text preprocessing to prepare raw email content for further NLP analysis. It begins by converting the entire text to lowercase to ensure uniformity and avoid treating the same word differently due to capitalization. Next, it removes all punctuation marks and numeric digits, which often do not contribute meaningful information to text classification tasks such as spam detection. The function also eliminates unnecessary whitespace by replacing multiple spaces with a single space and trimming any leading or trailing spaces. Overall, clean_text helps transform messy, raw text into a clean and simplified format, improving the effectiveness of tokenization, vectorization, and machine learning models.

In[]:
def clean_text(text):
    # Lowercase
    text = text.lower()
    # Remove punctuation
    text = text.translate(str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation))
    # Remove digits
    text = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text)
    # Remove extra spaces
    text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text).strip()

    return text

Tokenization + Stopwords Removal + Lemmatization:-

The preprocess_text function performs advanced text preprocessing to prepare email content for NLP modeling. It first calls the previously defined clean_text function to convert the text to lowercase, remove punctuation, digits, and extra spaces. The cleaned text is then tokenized into individual words using NLTKs word_tokenize. Common English stopwords are removed to reduce noise and retain only meaningful words. Each remaining token is tagged with its part-of-speech (POS) using NLTKs pos_tag function. Finally, the tokens are lemmatized using the WordNetLemmatizer, guided by the get_wordnet_pos function, which ensures that each word is reduced to its base form according to its correct POS category (e.g., verbs, nouns, adjectives). The lemmatized tokens are then joined back into a single string. This preprocessing pipeline helps standardize the text, reduce dimensionality, and improve the performance of machine learning models for spam detection.

In[]:
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

def preprocess_text(text):
    text = clean_text(text)
    tokens = word_tokenize(text)
    tokens = [w for w in tokens if w not in stop_words]
    tagged = nltk.pos_tag(tokens)
    lemmatized = [
        lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, get_wordnet_pos(pos))
        for word, pos in tagged
    ]
    return " ".join(lemmatized)

This code applies SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) to balance the class distribution in the training dataset. First, a SMOTE object is created with a fixed random seed to ensure reproducibility. The fit_resample method is then applied only to the training features (X_train) and labels (y_train), generating synthetic samples for the minority class (spam emails) to match the majority class (ham emails). The script prints the class distribution before and after SMOTE to demonstrate the effect of oversampling. Additionally, a side-by-side bar chart is created using Matplotlib, showing the count of each class before and after SMOTE. This visualization clearly illustrates how SMOTE balances the dataset, ensuring that the machine learning models are trained on a more equitable representation of both spam and non-spam emails, which helps improve model performance and reduces bias toward the majority class.

5. Model Building

Purpose of Model Building

Model building is a critical step in the spam detection project because it transforms the preprocessed and feature-engineered data into a predictive system capable of distinguishing between spam and legitimate emails. By applying machine learning algorithms such as Logistic Regression and Multinomial Naive Bayes, the model can learn complex patterns and relationships in the data, including word frequencies, rare words, capitalized words, and other engineered features. This allows the system to generalize from historical email examples and accurately classify new, unseen emails.

Importance of Model Building

The importance of model building lies in its ability to automate the decision-making process, improve accuracy, and reduce human effort in manually filtering spam emails. A well-trained model provides a scalable solution that can handle large volumes of email efficiently. Without model building, the insights gained from data preprocessing and feature engineering would remain descriptive and could not be effectively applied to real-world spam detection tasks. Machine learning models thus serve as the core mechanism for turning data into actionable predictions.
